<p>
  In the previous pod, we discussed what a theory is.
  A theory is a statement about how the universe works.
  The goal of physicists is to create theories,
  then run observations and experiments that can be explained
  and predicted by the theories.
  However, there is more to a good theory than simply matching
  the data.
  In this pod, we will learn about some of the qualities
  that make a theory strong: universality, parsimony, and clear limitations.
</p>

<h4>
  Universality
</h4>

<p>
    A good theory is <em>universal</em>, it applies in the entire universe, not just part of it.
    Of course, we cannot prove the entire universe follows a particular law unless we can visit and observe the entire
    universe, but a good theory should be applicable to all parts of the universe we can observe.
</p>

<h5>
    Example: Aristotle and Newton
</h5>

<p>
    Aristotle, and many thinkers after him, argued that earth and space (the heavens) followed fundamentally different laws.
    On earth, objects fall down and stop moving. In the heavens, they planets and starts move on their course forever.
    When Isaac Newton released his Laws of Gravity and Motion, he was able to describe motion both in earth and in space.
    Objects on earth fall down because they are attracted to the mass of the earth; planets and comets in space move in circles
    because they are pulled into those circles by the mass of the sun. In both cases, the Law of Gravity is followed.
    Objects on earth stop moving because, forces pull on them to stop them, but the absence of oif a force to stop them
    allows orbiting planets to continue moving. In both cases, forces are necessary tos top an object (Newton's First Law).
</p>

<p>
    The success of Newton's Laws was not simply that they were more correct, or that they better matched the data,
    but that they were more <strong>universal</strong>.
    With Aristotle's Laws, the different rules govern the earth and the heavens,
    but with Newton's Laws, the same rules govern both.
</p>

