<p>
    A good theory is <strong>parsimonious</strong>, which means that it explains the universe with <em>as few</em>
    and <em>as simple</em>
    basic assumptions as possible.
    Essentially, good theories are <strong>simple</strong>!
</p>

<h5>
    Example: Ptolemaic Universe vs. Kepler's Laws
</h5>

<p>
    The Greek philosopher Ptolemy created a model of the universe that was believed for centuries:
    all planets, as well as the sun and the moon, orbited the earth in circles.
    However, at times, people would see that a planet would be moving forward on its circular path,
    when, instead of completing its circle, it would suddenly start moving backwards!
    Astronomers and mathematicians invented a solution: the planets were not moving around the earth merely in circles,
    but in circles inside of circles, or even circles inside of circles inside of circles. With this modification,
    the Ptolemaic model was able to fit the observed data of planetary motion.
</p>

<p>
    In the 16th and 17th century, astronomers began to question Ptolemy's model.
    The Polish astronomer Nicolaus Copernicus was the first to posit that planets orbit the sun, not the earth,
    but the largest figure of this period was the German mathematician Johannes Kepler.
    By examining mountains of astronomical data compiled by the Danish astronomer Tycho Brahe,
    Kepler wrote three laws of planetary motion.
    The first was that all planets, earth included, move in an ellipse around the sun.
    (The other two are mathematical laws that determine the speed a planet moves.)
</p>

<p>
    Kepler's model could explain the problem with Ptolemy's:
    If Mars was moving in an apparent circle than suddenly turned around,
    it was not that mars had turned around, but that <em>the earth</em>
    had turned around and rotated the other way.
    There was no need to state that Mars was moving around the earth in a circle inside a circle inside of circle,
    only that Mars and Earth were both moving around the sun.
</p>

<p>
    Of course, today, we accept sun-centric theory, not the earth-centric theory,
    but the important question is <em>why</em> teh sun-centric theory is better.
    People might say it is because they one theory is correct and the other is wrong,
    but this is not the full story. If you assume planets move in circles inside of circles inside of circles,
    then this theory <em>still</em> matches the observed data from planets. It can still explain why each
    planet is seen int eh night sky at the particular place it is each night. So why was that theory abandoned?
</p>

<p>
    The sun-centric theory is superior because it is more <strong>parsimonius</strong>,
    meaning that it explains the motion of planets, correctly, with one simple assumption: that they all move around the sun.
    The earth-centric theory explains the motion of the planets but requires circles inside of circles inside of circles,
    which are far more complex.
    The sun-centric theory is superior because it is based on a single, straightforward, assumption.
</p>

