<h5>
    Example: The Electroweak Force
</h5>

<p>
    During the 20th century, physcists had discovered that all of the forces in the world, and thus the motion,
    could be broken in to four fundamental force:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        Gravity
    </li>
    <li>
        The Electromagnetic Force
    </li>
    <li>
        The Strong Nuclear Force
    </li>
    <li>
        The Weak Nuclear Force
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    In the 1960s and 1970s, Steven Weinberg, Sheldon Glashow, and Abdus Salam discovered that
    at high energies, the Electromagnetic Force and the Weak Nuclear Force
    combined to make a single force,
    called the <strong>electroweak force</strong>.
</p>
<p>
    This discovery made the theory of four fundamental forces more <em>parsimonious</em>.
    Before, all forces could be traced to four forces, now they could be traced to three.
    Fewer basic assumptions are necessary to explain the workings of the universe.
</p>

<p>
    Many physicists are still unsatisfied by having three fundamental forces and want their
    to be only one. A potential theory with only a single force would
    be called a <em>Grand Unified Theory</em> or a <em>Theory of Everything</em>.
    To date, no physicist has been able to create such a theory which matches experimental
    observations.
</p>

